
=============================
SINGLETON DESIGN PATTERN (C++ FULL INTERVIEW NOTES)
FROM BASIC → ADVANCED (WITH CODE)
=============================

========================================================
1. BASIC IDEA (WHAT + WHY)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Only ONE object of a class should exist
- Provide a global access point to that object

WHY:
- Controlled access to shared resource
- Avoid multiple instances (memory + consistency issues)

USE CASES:
- Logger
- Configuration manager
- Cache
- Driver manager
- Thread pool manager

========================================================
2. BASIC SINGLETON (LAZY - NOT THREAD SAFE)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Object created only when needed

CODE:
--------------------------------------------------------
class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton* instance;

    Singleton() {}  // private constructor

    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;

public:
    static Singleton* getInstance() {
        if (instance == nullptr) {
            instance = new Singleton();   // lazy init
        }
        return instance;
    }
};

Singleton* Singleton::instance = nullptr;
--------------------------------------------------------

PROBLEM:
- NOT thread-safe
- multiple threads → multiple objects possible

TIME:
O(1)

SPACE:
Heap object + static pointer

========================================================
3. THREAD SAFE (LOCK EVERY CALL - SIMPLE BUT SLOW)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Protect object creation using mutex

CODE:
--------------------------------------------------------
#include <mutex>

class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton* instance;
    static std::mutex mtx;

    Singleton() {}

    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;

public:
    static Singleton* getInstance() {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

        if (instance == nullptr) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
};

Singleton* Singleton::instance = nullptr;
std::mutex Singleton::mtx;
--------------------------------------------------------

PROBLEM:
- Every call locks mutex → performance overhead

TIME:
O(1) but slow due to locking

SPACE:
Heap + mutex

========================================================
4. DOUBLE CHECKED LOCKING (OPTIMIZED THREAD SAFE)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Avoid locking every time

CODE:
--------------------------------------------------------
#include <mutex>

class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton* instance;
    static std::mutex mtx;

    Singleton() {}

public:
    static Singleton* getInstance() {
        if (instance == nullptr) {
            std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

            if (instance == nullptr) {
                instance = new Singleton();
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
};

Singleton* Singleton::instance = nullptr;
std::mutex Singleton::mtx;
--------------------------------------------------------

PROBLEM:
- Complex
- Historically tricky (older C++ memory issues)

TIME:
Fast after initialization

SPACE:
Heap + mutex

========================================================
5. EAGER INITIALIZATION (ALWAYS CREATED)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Object created at program start

CODE:
--------------------------------------------------------
class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton instance;

    Singleton() {}

    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;

public:
    static Singleton& getInstance() {
        return instance;
    }
};

Singleton Singleton::instance;
--------------------------------------------------------

PROS:
- Thread-safe
- Simple

CONS:
- Created even if never used (waste memory)

TIME:
Created at startup

SPACE:
Always allocated

========================================================
6. MODERN BEST WAY (MOST IMPORTANT IN INTERVIEWS)
========================================================

IDEA:
- Static local variable inside function

CODE:
--------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>

class Singleton {
private:
    Singleton() {
        std::cout << "Constructor called\n";
    }

    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;

public:
    static Singleton& getInstance() {
        static Singleton instance;  // lazy + thread-safe (C++11+)
        return instance;
    }

    void show() {
        std::cout << "Hello Singleton\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Singleton& s1 = Singleton::getInstance();
    Singleton& s2 = Singleton::getInstance();

    s1.show();

    if (&s1 == &s2) {
        std::cout << "Same instance\n";
    }
}
--------------------------------------------------------

WHY BEST:
- Lazy initialization
- Thread-safe (C++11 guarantee)
- No mutex
- No manual memory management
- No leaks

TIME:
O(1)

SPACE:
Single static object

========================================================
7. COMPARISON TABLE (VERY IMPORTANT)
========================================================

LAZY (RAW POINTER):
- Fast ❌ not thread-safe

LOCK EVERY CALL:
- Safe ❌ slow

DOUBLE CHECKED LOCKING:
- Safe ⚠️ complex

EAGER:
- Safe ⚠️ wastes memory

STATIC LOCAL (BEST):
- Safe ✔️ fast ✔️ lazy ✔️ simple ✔️

========================================================
8. INTERVIEW ONE-LINER SUMMARY
========================================================

- Singleton ensures ONE object only
- Lazy = create when needed
- Best modern approach = static local instance
